    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-04-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-04-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="966"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d966">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> files,
                    lot 63 D 351, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 150 Series</note>
                <head>No. 966<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Statement of Policy by the National Security Council</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d966fn1">Attached to the source text were a cover sheet; a
                        note by the Executive Secretary of the National Security Council, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LAYJSJ1">James S. Lay, Jr.</persName>, dated Apr. 23,
                        informing the Council of the President’s approval of <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 150/1; and a memorandum by <persName corresp="#p_LAYJSJ1"
                            >Lay</persName> dated Apr. 27 announcing the declassification of this
                        statement of policy on that date, none printed. <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 150 was approved by the Council during its 140th meeting on
                        Apr. 22, subject to the revision of paragraph 3. The revised statement of
                        policy was then approved by President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> on Apr. 23 and issued as <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 150/1. As indicated in <persName corresp="#p_LAYJSJ1"
                            >Lay</persName>’s memorandum of Apr. 27, it was then released to the
                        press 4 days later. (<gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>–<gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> files, lot 63 D 351, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 150 Series)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 150/1</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-04-23">April 23,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">National Security Interests in the St. <persName
                            corresp="#p_VASSLC1">Lawrence</persName>–Great Lakes Seaway Project</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Early initiation and completion of the St. <persName corresp="#p_VASSLC1"
                            >Lawrence</persName>–Great Lakes Seaway is in the interest of national
                        security.</item>
                    <pb facs="0988" n="2078" xml:id="pg_2078"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The United States should promptly take whatever action may be appropriate
                        to clear the way for commencement of the project, whether by Canada alone
                        or, now or as may be later developed, by Canada and the United States
                        jointly.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>It is desirable that the U.S. participate in the construction of the
                        Seaway; the extent of and limitations upon such participation to be the
                        subject of separate determination by authority other than the National
                        Security Council.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
